post_text:
WELCOME BACK!

As we prepare to begin the school year online, we need once again to hear from you. When we sent out a survey in the spring, we thought we would definitely be back in the building with students in September. We are unable to do that right now but, with fingers crossed, we are hoping to work toward that goal. The information you gave us confirmed what we also wanted, students in school! Now I am asking you to take another short survey so we can make changes in how we do online instruction. Our staff is already working hard to make sure things go smoothly for all students. You can access the survey at the following link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/YC78TV7

Thank you for your continued support!

Laura

post_text:
Good afternoon all! We hope this message finds you all happy and healthy after a wonderful 4th of July. Our 20-21 COVID Task-force is starting to get some traction on a reopening plan for the new school year. The task force has met numerous times since this pandemic hit and are sifting through all the data sent down from the state and OPSI. As many school districts in our area fight to keep some normalcy to their schedules, we can not thank our community and parents enough for all their support. We received a large amount of input through our online survey and will be using that data to shape how the district will reopen. We are hoping to have some concrete details out to our parents and community members as soon as next week.

Make sure to stay tuned for details on the opening for the 20-21 school year. #WCstrong.

As always, stay safe, stay healthy, stay well.

post_text: As we wrap out the 2019-2020 school year we have started to process fines for missing school items. :( This year we have a high amount of missing text books, library books and electronic devices. Please, take a moment to look around your house, your car even forgot backpacks to see if you may have a few of these items. Any books can be dropped off at the bus garage through the homework return slot. If you need to return an electronic device, please call the office at 509-345-2541 to set up a time. DO NOT, we repeat, DO NOT drop electronic devices through the homework return slot. Fines will be processed and sent the week of June 22nd. All fines must be paid or school property returned before the district can release your students year end grades.

post_text: Good morning Wilson Creekers! We are still working through some technical difficulties evolving Zoom and Google Classroom. We have found out that even though it feels great to scream at your current device, shake it around and set it back down **gently** simply will not help. At this time, we ask everyone to take a step back, go outside and enjoy the sun. We are working through the kinks and will reach out to student, parents and guardians as soon as we have some answers. We are all in this together and no student will be left behind. We are #WCstrong and we will prevail.

Dear Parents and Guardians,

It is that time of year again when we are preparing for conferences so that we can share with you our data and observations about your student’s growth. This year conferences will be the week of November 12th through the 14th, with the night of the 14th being open until 7:00. I have asked the elementary staff to have letters out with times and schedules by Monday, October 21st and then follow up with a letter home in the folders. The secondary letters will be mailed home on the 21st as well. Elementary conferences will take place in the classrooms, while secondary conferences will take place in the high school commons. We look forward to meeting with you and your students and thank you for taking the time to help us create a team of effort to help support your child in his/her learning.

Warmly, Sally Nelson

post_text:
Parents,
I am sending this notice out based on a decision for the safety of our students, staff and parents. As we are in a unique location, weather can be seen and unseen...with that said, when I have traveled the roads, our supervisor of transportation has traveled the roads and our staff and parents have traveled the roads deeming them treacherous, we must look to close school. School districts in the vicinity with whom we are combined are closed, I do not think it is safe to run our buses and have school. We have faced some very bad weather and tomorrow will serve to be a cleanup day with no promised time frame for road safety cleanup... therefore, a two-hour delay will not suffice. I am making a decision to close our schools out of respect for the department of transportation an any emergency personnel who answer to calls. We will keep you posted on days we may need to make up and days waived due to the state of emergency governor Inslee has addressed.

Please stay home and be safe.

Principal Sally Nelson

post_text:
Good afternoon everyone,
As you may be aware, we are working aggressively this year to make Family Access a better source of information to our families. With that said, we are moving forward with the Skyalert application! 😊 This application involves merging School Messenger and Family Access together. In order to complete the process to merge/sync the two systems, we will be taking School Messenger offline for two weeks. Starting Thursday, October 4th through the 18th, the system will be taken offline and Food Service and Attendance notifications will not be sent out.
The changes to the Skyward system will open up a number of ways to communicate with our families and will streamline the systems we currently have. This process will allow families to have access to their personal preference settings regarding notifications right from their Skyward Family Access account. Additional information will be posted on our district website once the system is back online.

Thank you and have a great night.

Stacy
